Pre-heat your oven to 220 degrees. Remove the core from each of the @red pepper{1}, @yellow pepper{1/2} and @green pepper{1} and chop them into chunky slices. Coarsely chop the @coriander{3} and finely chop the @red onion{1}(finely chopped). Lastly, drain and rinse the @mixed beans{1}.

Coat the peppers in @olive oil{1%tsp} and a good pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Place on a #baking tray{} and put in the oven for ~{20%minutes}, or until they're soft and a little crispy around the edges.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a medium-sized #frying pan{} on medium-low heat. Cook the red onion for ~{5%minutes} then add @salt{1/4%tsp} and a pinch of pepper. Add in the mixed beans, @habanero sauce{2}, @cumin{1} tsp, @tomato puree{2} tbsp and @water{5%tbsp}. Cook with a #lid{} on for ~{15%minutes}.

Grate @lime{1/4%tsp}(zested) into the @sour cream{1/2}. Squeeze in @lime juice{1/2%tsp} and add a little pinch of salt and pepper. Give it all a good stir and keep it for later.

> Make enquiries on the internet to have a mariachi band come to dinner.

== Refried Beans ==

To make your refried beans, take out two-thirds of the cooked beans from the #pan{} and mash them to a paste using the back of a #fork{}. Now mix the remaining whole beans into the paste (so you have two textures). Check for seasoning and voila, they're done!

== Assembly ==

Put the @super soft tortillas with whole wheat{4} in the oven for ~{2%minutes} to warm them. We like to serve the peppers, bean mix and sour cream in separate #bowls{} so everyone can dive in. Alternatively you can add the ingredients to the tortillas, roll them up in the kitchen and send them out to the camp fire! Don't forget a good dollop of your citrus sour cream and garnish with plenty of coriander.

> Mexican food has been up and coming for a while now with its combinations of citrus flavours, spices and the complimentary textures of soft beans and crunchy peppers. This citrus soured cream is the perfect cooling topping!